WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:06.320
<v Speaker 1>There are also some variations that you might come across in dialect.

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:12.480
<v Speaker 1>For example, in most of Spain they use le and les.

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:23.060
<v Speaker 1>Whenever they're referring to him or her or you formal or you guys or them, so instead of la and la and los and las.

00:00:22.740 --> 00:00:28.740
<v Speaker 1>They're using le and les, not just to make to him, to her.

00:00:28.740 --> 00:00:32.180
<v Speaker 1>They will use it always when they're referring to people and not things.

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:33.700
<v Speaker 1>So in most of Spain

00:00:33.580 --> 00:00:43.500
<v Speaker 1>Leveo means I see him, her or you formal, and loveo means I see it, but in the great majority of the Spanish-speaking world this isn't the case.

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:53.199
<v Speaker 1>In most of Spain you have vosotros, which is the U plural informal, which is only used in Spain or most of Spain

00:00:53.320 --> 00:01:00.920
<v Speaker 1>But again, nowhere in Latin America, so that might be something you want to listen out for if you will practice this dialect of Spanish

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:13.860
<v Speaker 1>Many accents have an aspirated S in Spanish, so you might hear esta instead of esta instead of como está, espero instead of espero

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:28.400
<v Speaker 1>Around the Rio de la Plata, for example, around Montevideo and Buenos Aires, and in 30% of the Spanish-speaking world used exclusively or mixed with tú, you also have dos.

00:01:28.220 --> 00:01:30.140
<v Speaker 1>Bos, another word for tu.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:33.500
<v Speaker 1>And the verb conjugations might change slightly.

00:01:33.500 --> 00:01:37.980
<v Speaker 1>So instead of puedes, you might hear podes.

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:41.260
<v Speaker 1>And because the accent's coming on the end, that O isn't splitting.

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:48.380
<v Speaker 1>So you might come across small differences.

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:56.220
<v Speaker 1>in different dialects of Spanish but they are minor and you now have all of the know-how and experience to identify

00:01:56.240 --> 00:02:07.440
<v Speaker 1>and understand them and if you want adopt them you can adopt these differences it's advisable to speak like the people you are practicing with because the more you speak like

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:11.680
<v Speaker 1>the Spanish that you are hearing, the more you understand.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:20.640
<v Speaker 1>Now if you're talking with people from different Spanish speaking countries, people with different dialects or accents in Spanish, then you might get

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:24.040
<v Speaker 1>something like a pan-Hispanic accent, let's say.

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:33.240
<v Speaker 1>Like many native Spanish speakers who move around the Spanish speaking world or spend time with Spanish speakers from different countries also have.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:39.920
<v Speaker 1>You might even find yourself switching between different accents when you're talking with people from different places.

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:45.280
<v Speaker 1>Again, a phenomenon that we also find occurring amongst native speakers

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:48.220
<v Speaker 1>Ahora hablamos español.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:51.180
<v Speaker 1>Ahora somos hispanohablantes.

00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:52.380
<v Speaker 1>Now we speak Spanish.

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:54.220
<v Speaker 1>Now we are Spanish speakers.

00:02:54.220 --> 00:02:56.620
<v Speaker 1>Somos hispanohablantes.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:59.820
<v Speaker 1>Y solo tenemos que practicar.

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:07.440
<v Speaker 1>hablar y analizar para perfeccionar nuestro español

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:16.640
<v Speaker 1>My advice now for the end of the course is to spend some time practicing, to get out and practice and expose yourself to Spanish as much as possible.

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:23.920
<v Speaker 1>And then maybe after a short while of practicing you might want to repeat the course to refresh and touch up on anything that

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:32.260
<v Speaker 1>You might be unsure of, especially having practiced and being solid on so many things, it will really free up a lot of mental space

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:45.260
<v Speaker 1>to home in on the things that you are more uncertain with and in this way repeating the course might be a little bit like when you watch a good movie twice and on the second time round you have a different experience

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:55.020
<v Speaker 1>The most important thing in this journey of exploring and improving your Spanish is to not to forget to enjoy it.

00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:59.300
<v Speaker 1>to not obsess with the destination but to enjoy the journey.

00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:03.700
<v Speaker 1>You are already a Spanish speaker, you should enjoy it.

00:04:03.620 --> 00:04:15.220
<v Speaker 1>There is a huge variety of literature, music and cinema coming from Spanish-speaking countries, so you can enjoy this and at the same time effectively be studying.

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:16.980
<v Speaker 1>But it won't feel like that

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:20.840
<v Speaker 1>And we must bear in mind also that listening is a separate skill.

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:27.160
<v Speaker 1>You will hear many things that you could think your way through and say and maybe not understand them.

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:34.440
<v Speaker 1>So when you first begin listening, don't be overwhelmed by the fact that you don't understand at the beginning as much as you can speak.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:39.720
<v Speaker 1>All you have to do is insist on analyzing the language that you're exposed to.

00:04:39.539 --> 00:04:49.060
<v Speaker 1>breaking it up and seeing what you can learn from that and although at the beginning it will seem very fast once you get in the habit of this analysis

00:04:49.340 --> 00:05:01.420
<v Speaker 1>And this breaking up of the language in the same way that we were doing when we were building up to create our sentences in reverse, deconstructing what you hear, the more you do this

00:05:01.539 --> 00:05:04.340
<v Speaker 1>the most Spanish will slow down.

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:08.740
<v Speaker 1>It would slow right down and you will hear a lot more.

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:09.060
<v Speaker 1>So

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:14.540
<v Speaker 1>Like I said, don't be overwhelmed by not understanding a lot at the beginning.

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:15.340
<v Speaker 1>Insist.

00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:16.380
<v Speaker 1>Enjoy music.

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:18.620
<v Speaker 1>Watch movies with subtitles.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:26.280
<v Speaker 1>Try to match between the subtitles in English and what you are hearing in Spanish and just try to match bits and pieces

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:34.400
<v Speaker 1>If you insist with this very quickly, you will notice that you are understanding a lot more and that the language appears to slow right down.

